    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-04-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-04-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="22"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 E.W./4–2845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-04-28T00:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 28, 1945—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received April 29—9:50
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2199. For Matthews<note n="22" xml:id="d22fn22">H. Freeman Matthews, Director of
                        the Office of European Affairs.</note> from Murphy.<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d22fn23">Robert D. Murphy, United States Political Adviser for
                        Germany.</note> Reference my letter of April 16. The Department will be
                    interested in SHAEF cable to Combined Chiefs of Staff Scaf 314 April 27
                    regarding truce in Holland. Latest developments are that two Generals from
                    British 21st Army Group will enter into contact today with representatives of
                    Seyss-Inquart. Discussions will be initially limited to question of food
                    supplies for Holland. It has apparently not yet been decided when and if SHAEF
                    will later take part in discussions. In meantime pending negotiations dropping
                    of food by air will be begun today.</p>
                <p>Russians have replied through military mission Moscow they have studied
                    conditions of discussion with the Germans and would like to add one more namely
                    that the German command be obligated not to transfer its troops to other parts
                    of the front including the Russian front during the entire period of proposed
                    armistice. [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
